results.title: The black footed ferret reintroduction
results.description: The map shows the suitable areas for black-footed ferret reintroduction in Northeast Colorado. Based on the criteria: the habitats of prairie dogs and the disturbance of roads and cities. Black-footed ferret need to survive in grassland and prairie dog habitat, and can not survive in 1 mile of roads and 5 miles of cities areas.There are three layers in the map, the suitable area for black-footed ferret reintroduction, the three largest suitable areas and northeast Colorado boundary.
results.snippet: The suitable areas for Black footed ferret reintroduction in northeast Colorado

results.name: CO_PODs_Vegetation_WTL1
results.title: CO_PODs_Vegetation_WTL1
results.description:
In the Colorado WRA, the Vegetation dataset is used to support the development of the Surface Fuels, Canopy Cover, Canopy Stand Height, Canopy Base Height, and Canopy Bulk Density datasets.

The 2014 LANDFIRE program data product (Existing Vegetation Type) was used to compile the Vegetation data for the West Wide Risk Assessment and the Colorado WRA. This reflects data current to 2014. Some modifications were completed to reflect recent disturbances such as large wildfires and pine beetle infestations prevalent in central Colorado over recent years. The LANDFIRE EVT data was classified to reflect general vegetation cover types for representation with CO-WRAP.

results.title: Land-Use Change in Samut Songkhram, Thailand
results.description: Uncontrolled growth of shrimp farms in the 1980s resulted in the decimation of valuable mangrove ecosystems. In the early 1990s, laws and regulations were implemented which slowed the destruction of the remaining healthy vegetation along the coast. In recent years, some areas have had success with restoration efforts. These areas should be the focus of continued conservation education and monitoring practices.
results.snippet: This application shows the patterns of land-use change in Samut Songkhram, Thailand, over the last 40 years.

results.title: Living in Sydney
results.description: After I graduate in May I will be moving to Sydney to live and start my career. I created this map to help me chose a location to begin searching for apartment buildings/places to live. This decision will be based upon the proximity to the jobs I am applying for and the ability to walk, bike, or ride a train to work as I will not be owning a car while I live in Sydney. Another aspect I love about the city of Sydney is its gorgeous outdoor areas and botanical gardens. In order to encompass all of my criteria for making this decision, this map displays potential job locations, community gardens, and the bike lanes and train stations/lines in Sydney.

results.name: WildfireRisk_tif
results.title: WildfireRisk_tif
results.description:
Wildfire Risk identifies areas with the greatest potential impacts from a wildfire –i.e. those areas most at risk when considering the four values layers. The Values at Risk Rating is a key component of Wildfire Risk. It is comprised of several individual risk layers including Wildland Urban Interface (housing density), Forest Assets, Riparian Assets and Drinking Water Importance Areas risk outputs. The WUI component is a key element of the composite risk since it represents where people live in the wildland and urban fringe areas that are susceptible to wildfires and damages. The four individual risk layers are weighted to derive the Values at Risk Rating layer.

The risk map is derived at a 30-meter resolution. This scale of data was chosen to be consistent with the accuracy of the primary surface fuels dataset used in the assessment. While not appropriate for site specific analysis, it is appropriate for regional, county or local planning efforts.
results.snippet: Wildfire Risk is a composite risk map created by combining the Values at Risk Rating and the Burn Probability layers.

results.title: Rifle Ranch Riparian Restoration
results.description:
Welcome to Rifle Ranch, a living lab for riparian restoration on Colorado's Western Slope! Since 2016, the Colorado Natural Heritage Program (CNHP) has partnered with Rifle Ranch to enhance the habitat value and ecological condition of the Rifle Creek riparian area while promoting conservation learning and training opportunities for future generations of students, interns, and restoration practitioners in the Rifle Creek Watershed. 

Learn more about CNHP's riparian restoration process, the larger Rifle Creek watershed, animals and plants of Rifle Ranch, and the community involvement at Rifle Ranch as you explore this story map!
results.snippet: Welcome to Rifle Ranch, a living lab for riparian restoration on Colorado's Western Slope.
